#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:4
msgid "Logging"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:9
msgid ""
"pytest captures log messages of level ``WARNING`` or above automatically and "
"displays them in their own section for each failed test in the same manner "
"as captured stdout and stderr."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:12
msgid "Running without options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:14
msgid "pytest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:18 ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:41
msgid "Shows failed tests like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:20
msgid ""
"----------------------- Captured stdlog call ----------------------\n"
"test_reporting.py    26 WARNING  text going to logger\n"
"----------------------- Captured stdout call ----------------------\n"
"text going to stdout\n"
"----------------------- Captured stderr call ----------------------\n"
"text going to stderr\n"
"==================== 2 failed in 0.02 seconds ====================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:30
msgid ""
"By default each captured log message shows the module, line number, log "
"level and message."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:33
msgid ""
"If desired the log and date format can be specified to anything that the "
"logging module supports by passing specific formatting options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:36
msgid ""
"pytest --log-format=\"%(asctime)s %(levelname)s %(message)s\" \\\n"
"        --log-date-format=\"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:43
msgid ""
"----------------------- Captured stdlog call ----------------------\n"
"2010-04-10 14:48:44 WARNING text going to logger\n"
"----------------------- Captured stdout call ----------------------\n"
"text going to stdout\n"
"----------------------- Captured stderr call ----------------------\n"
"text going to stderr\n"
"==================== 2 failed in 0.02 seconds ====================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:53
msgid "These options can also be customized through ``pytest.ini`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:55
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"log_format = %(asctime)s %(levelname)s %(message)s\n"
"log_date_format = %Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:61
msgid ""
"Further it is possible to disable reporting of captured content (stdout, "
"stderr and logs) on failed tests completely with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:64
msgid "pytest --show-capture=no"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:70
msgid "caplog fixture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:72
msgid ""
"Inside tests it is possible to change the log level for the captured log "
"messages.  This is supported by the ``caplog`` fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:75
msgid ""
"def test_foo(caplog):\n"
"    caplog.set_level(logging.INFO)\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:81
msgid ""
"By default the level is set on the root logger, however as a convenience it "
"is also possible to set the log level of any logger:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:85
msgid ""
"def test_foo(caplog):\n"
"    caplog.set_level(logging.CRITICAL, logger=\"root.baz\")\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:91
msgid "The log levels set are restored automatically at the end of the test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:93
msgid ""
"It is also possible to use a context manager to temporarily change the log "
"level inside a ``with`` block:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:96
msgid ""
"def test_bar(caplog):\n"
"    with caplog.at_level(logging.INFO):\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:102
msgid ""
"Again, by default the level of the root logger is affected but the level of "
"any logger can be changed instead with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:105
msgid ""
"def test_bar(caplog):\n"
"    with caplog.at_level(logging.CRITICAL, logger=\"root.baz\"):\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:111
msgid ""
"Lastly all the logs sent to the logger during the test run are made "
"available on the fixture in the form of both the ``logging.LogRecord`` "
"instances and the final log text. This is useful for when you want to assert "
"on the contents of a message:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:115
msgid ""
"def test_baz(caplog):\n"
"    func_under_test()\n"
"    for record in caplog.records:\n"
"        assert record.levelname != \"CRITICAL\"\n"
"    assert \"wally\" not in caplog.text"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:123
msgid ""
"For all the available attributes of the log records see the ``logging."
"LogRecord`` class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:126
msgid ""
"You can also resort to ``record_tuples`` if all you want to do is to ensure, "
"that certain messages have been logged under a given logger name with a "
"given severity and message:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:130
msgid ""
"def test_foo(caplog):\n"
"    logging.getLogger().info(\"boo %s\", \"arg\")\n"
"\n"
"    assert caplog.record_tuples == [(\"root\", logging.INFO, \"boo arg\")]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:137
msgid ""
"You can call ``caplog.clear()`` to reset the captured log records in a test:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:139
msgid ""
"def test_something_with_clearing_records(caplog):\n"
"    some_method_that_creates_log_records()\n"
"    caplog.clear()\n"
"    your_test_method()\n"
"    assert [\"Foo\"] == [rec.message for rec in caplog.records]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:148
msgid ""
"The ``caplog.records`` attribute contains records from the current stage "
"only, so inside the ``setup`` phase it contains only setup logs, same with "
"the ``call`` and ``teardown`` phases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:152
msgid ""
"To access logs from other stages, use the ``caplog.get_records(when)`` "
"method. As an example, if you want to make sure that tests which use a "
"certain fixture never log any warnings, you can inspect the records for the "
"``setup`` and ``call`` stages during teardown like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:156
msgid ""
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def window(caplog):\n"
"    window = create_window()\n"
"    yield window\n"
"    for when in (\"setup\", \"call\"):\n"
"        messages = [\n"
"            x.message for x in caplog.get_records(when) if x.levelno == "
"logging.WARNING\n"
"        ]\n"
"        if messages:\n"
"            pytest.fail(\n"
"                \"warning messages encountered during testing: {}\"."
"format(messages)\n"
"            )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:173
msgid ""
"The full API is available at :class:`_pytest.logging.LogCaptureFixture`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:179
msgid "Live Logs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:181
msgid ""
"By setting the :confval:`log_cli` configuration option to ``true``, pytest "
"will output logging records as they are emitted directly into the console."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:184
msgid ""
"You can specify the logging level for which log records with equal or higher "
"level are printed to the console by passing ``--log-cli-level``. This "
"setting accepts the logging level names as seen in python's documentation or "
"an integer as the logging level num."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:189
msgid ""
"Additionally, you can also specify ``--log-cli-format`` and ``--log-cli-date-"
"format`` which mirror and default to ``--log-format`` and ``--log-date-"
"format`` if not provided, but are applied only to the console logging "
"handler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:194
msgid ""
"All of the CLI log options can also be set in the configuration INI file. "
"The option names are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:197
msgid "``log_cli_level``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:198
msgid "``log_cli_format``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:199
msgid "``log_cli_date_format``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:201
msgid ""
"If you need to record the whole test suite logging calls to a file, you can "
"pass ``--log-file=/path/to/log/file``. This log file is opened in write mode "
"which means that it will be overwritten at each run tests session."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:205
msgid ""
"You can also specify the logging level for the log file by passing ``--log-"
"file-level``. This setting accepts the logging level names as seen in "
"python's documentation(ie, uppercased level names) or an integer as the "
"logging level num."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:210
msgid ""
"Additionally, you can also specify ``--log-file-format`` and ``--log-file-"
"date-format`` which are equal to ``--log-format`` and ``--log-date-format`` "
"but are applied to the log file logging handler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:214
msgid ""
"All of the log file options can also be set in the configuration INI file. "
"The option names are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:217
msgid "``log_file``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:218
msgid "``log_file_level``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:219
msgid "``log_file_format``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:220
msgid "``log_file_date_format``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:222
msgid ""
"You can call ``set_log_path()`` to customize the log_file path dynamically. "
"This functionality is considered **experimental**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:228
msgid "Release notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:230
msgid ""
"This feature was introduced as a drop-in replacement for the `pytest-"
"catchlog <https://pypi.org/project/pytest-catchlog/>`_ plugin and they "
"conflict with each other. The backward compatibility API with ``pytest-"
"capturelog`` has been dropped when this feature was introduced, so if for "
"that reason you still need ``pytest-catchlog`` you can disable the internal "
"feature by adding to your ``pytest.ini``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:237
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"    addopts=-p no:logging"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:246
msgid "Incompatible changes in pytest 3.4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:248
msgid ""
"This feature was introduced in ``3.3`` and some **incompatible changes** "
"have been made in ``3.4`` after community feedback:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:251
msgid ""
"Log levels are no longer changed unless explicitly requested by the :confval:"
"`log_level` configuration or ``--log-level`` command-line options. This "
"allows users to configure logger objects themselves."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:253
msgid ""
":ref:`Live Logs <live_logs>` is now disabled by default and can be enabled "
"setting the :confval:`log_cli` configuration option to ``true``. When "
"enabled, the verbosity is increased so logging for each test is visible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:256
msgid ""
":ref:`Live Logs <live_logs>` are now sent to ``sys.stdout`` and no longer "
"require the ``-s`` command-line option to work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:259
msgid ""
"If you want to partially restore the logging behavior of version ``3.3``, "
"you can add this options to your ``ini`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:262
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"log_cli=true\n"
"log_level=NOTSET"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/logging.rst:268
msgid ""
"More details about the discussion that lead to this changes can be read in "
"issue `#3013 <https://github.com/pytest-dev/pytest/issues/3013>`_."
msgstr ""
